Opening: Why Real Clients Matter
[presentation] Welcome architects and introduce the concept of designing for real clients with real families, real budgets and real problems. Share pre-assigned client contacts.

First Principles of Comfort
[presentation] Cover key concepts: thermal comfort basics, humidity and health, natural ventilation, daylight vs. heat gain, privacy vs. openness. Ground all design decisions in these fundamentals.

text:
Architecture
2
Opening: Learning from the Past
[presentation] Introduce the value of traditional Iraqi architecture for solving modern comfort problems. Show examples of vernacular solutions that worked without electricity. Connect to client problems identified on Day 1.

metadata.purpose: [presentation] Introduce the value of traditional Iraqi architecture for solving modern comfort problems. Show examples of vernacular solutions that worked without electricity. Connect to client problems identified on Day 1.

text:
Architecture
2
Traditional Cooling Systems Deep Dive
[presentation] Cover key traditional systems: wind catchers (badgir), courtyards and thermal mass, shading devices (mashrabiya), evaporative cooling, thermal chimneys, and underground spaces. Explain the physics behind each system and why it worked. Show photos from Old Mosul and other Iraqi cities.

metadata.purpose: [presentation] Cover key traditional systems: wind catchers (badgir), courtyards and thermal mass, shading devices (mashrabiya), evaporative cooling, thermal chimneys, and underground spaces. Explain the physics behind each system and why it worked. Show photos from Old Mosul and other Iraqi cities.

text:
Architecture
2
Heritage Principle Extraction
[group_work] In small groups, analyze 3 traditional buildings (photos provided). For each, identify: What problem did it solve? What principle did it use? What made it work? Complete Workbook Section E: Heritage Analysis with at least 10 extracted principles.

metadata.purpose: [group_work] In small groups, analyze 3 traditional buildings (photos provided). For each, identify: What problem did it solve? What principle did it use? What made it work? Complete Workbook Section E: Heritage Analysis with at least 10 extracted principles.

text:

2
Old City Heritage Walk
[field_work] Guided walk through Old Mosul (or heritage district). Document 5 traditional features with photos and sketches. For each feature: photograph, sketch key details, measure if possible, note materials used, identify cooling/ventilation principle, assess current condition. Record in workbook with evidence photos.

Create matrix with columns: Heritage Principle | Problem It Solved | Modern Material/Method | Local Supplier | Estimated Cost. Research local suppliers via phone/WhatsApp to get actual quotes for materials.
